<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06048078 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06048078 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PAST; NICARAGUA; OPPOSE; GOVERNMENT; LEADER; SHOOTING; DEATH  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Former Contra leader Enrique Bermudez was shot and killed Saturday night by anunidentified gunman as he stepped out of his car in front of a downtown hotel,witnesses said.;    Bermudez, 58, a member of the Contra directorate that hadwaged war against the former Sandinista government, was shot once in the head.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FORMER CONTRA LEADER KILLED OUTSIDE HOTEL  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The assailant fled on foot, said Associated Press correspondent FiladelfoAleman, who happened to be at the scene.;    Assistant Police Chief AlvaroGuzman confirmed Bermudez was killed and that investigators had no suspects inthe shooting, which occurred at about 11 p.m. (9 p.m. PST).;    Bermudez hadbeen based in Miami for years but returned to Managua shortly afterconservative President Violeta Chamorro was elected Feb. 25, 1990.;    TheContras and the United States had backed her campaign, and the rebels agreedto a cease-fire with Chamorro on April 19, six days before she took office.;   But Bermudez recently had criticized her government for allegedly not payingattention to the needs of former Contras.;    He returned to Managua on Oct.18 to live in Nicaragua and recover property that he said had been confiscatedduring the Sandinista rule.;    He had not been active in politics until thepast few weeks, when he met with former Contra fighters and said he would helpthem organize to press the government with their demands for housing, land andmoney to rebuild their lives.;    He was ousted as the rebels' top militaryleader in February 1990 after weathering years of infighting and accusationsof corruption and human-rights violations.;    Bermudez had run theU.S.-backed Contra army in one post or another until his ouster. He remained amilitary officer after that, but had no responsibilities.;    Contra officialssaid at the time that Bermudez's ouster was intended as a signal to theSandinista government and was not a rejection of Bermudez.;    The Sandinistasand some human-rights organizations had accused Contra troops under Bermudezof killing two nuns, one a U.S. citizen, in an attack on a church vehicle innorthern Nicaragua in January 1990.;    The Contras blamed the Sandinistagovernment.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Managua, Nicaragua  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910217  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  351  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday February 17, 199100048078,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>